.SH "struct pdg::KeyEvent"
.PP 
a key down or up event 

Generated by the EventManager when the user pushes down on a key (\fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyDown\fP) or releases a key (\fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyUp\fP)\&. Use this for arcade style key handling\&.

.PP
For keyboard data entry, use \fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyPress\fP\&. 
.PP
.nf
{ 
    emitter: {},       // the emitter that generated this event
    eventType: 4,      // the event type (eventType_KeyUp or eventType_KeyDown)
    keyCode: 34        // the raw key code from the OS
} 

.fi
.PP

.PP
\fBPlatform-Specific Key Codes\fP
.RS 4

.RE
.PP
The \fRkeyCode\fP field contains \fBplatform-specific raw hardware keycodes\fP from the operating system:
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBMac OS X\fP: Hardware scan codes from NSEvent (e\&.g\&., 56 for left shift)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBWindows\fP: Virtual key codes (VK_* constants, e\&.g\&., 0xA0 for left shift)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBLinux/GLFW\fP: GLFW scan codes
.PP

.PP
\fBWarning\fP
.RS 4
If you need to check for specific keys in a cross-platform way, use \fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyPress\fP events instead, which provide unicode character codes\&. However, modifier keys (shift, control, alt, meta) do not generate KeyPress events, so PDG provides platform-specific constants (see \fBKey Code Constants\fP) that allow you to write cross-platform code for detecting modifier key presses:
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBpdg\&.keyCode_LeftShift\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_RightShift\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_Shift\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBpdg\&.keyCode_LeftControl\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_RightControl\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_Control\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBpdg\&.keyCode_LeftAlt\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_RightAlt\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_Alt\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBpdg\&.keyCode_LeftMeta\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_RightMeta\fP, \fBpdg\&.keyCode_Meta\fP
.PP
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyDown\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyUp\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyPress\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.onKeyDown()\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.EventManager\&.isKeyDown()\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.EventManager\&.isRawKeyDown()\fP 
.RE
.PP

.SH "struct pdg::KeyPressEvent"
.PP 
the user pressed and released a key 

Generated by the EventManager when the user presses and releases a key (a keystroke)\&. Also generated by repeat key events from the OS when a key is held down\&.

.PP
For arcade style multi-key handling see \fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyDown\fP and \fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyUp\fP\&. 
.PP
.nf
{ 
    emitter: {},            // the emitter that generated this event
    eventType: 6,           // the event type (eventType_KeyPress)
    shift: false,           // true if the shift key is held down
    ctrl: false,            // true if the control key is held down
    alt: false,             // true if the alt (or option) key is held down
    meta: false,            // true if the meta (windows or command) key is held down
    unicode: 48,            // the Unicode character code generated by this key
    isRepeating: false,     // true if this is a repeat key event
} 

.fi
.PP

.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBpdg\&.eventType_KeyPress\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.onKeyPress()\fP 

.PP
\fBKey Code Constants\fP 
.RE
.PP

.SH "struct pdg::MouseEvent"
.PP 
the user did something with the mouse 

Generated by the EventManager whenever the user moves the mouse (\fBpdg\&.eventType_MouseMove\fP) or clicks a mouse button (\fBpdg\&.eventType_MouseDown\fP and \fBpdg\&.eventType_MouseUp\fP)\&.

.PP
The EventManager also tracks the state of the mouse buttons, so you can retrieve that at any time with \fBpdg\&.EventManager\&.isButtonDown()\fP\&. The GraphicsManager tracks the position of the mouse, and that can be retrieved at any time with \fBpdg\&.GraphicsManager\&.getMouse()\fP\&. 
.PP
.nf
{ 
    emitter: {},            // the emitter that generated this event
    eventType: 7,           // the event type (eventType_MouseUp|Down|Move)
    shift: false,           // true if the shift key is held down
    ctrl: false,            // true if the control key is held down
    alt: false,             // true if the alt (or option) key is held down
    meta: false,            // true if the meta (windows or command) key is held down
    mousePos: {
        x: 456,                         // the x coordinate of the mouse when the event occurred
        y: 201              // the y coordinate of the mouse when the event occurred
    },
    leftButton: false,      // true if the left mouse button was down
    rightButton: false,     // true if the right mouse button was down
    buttonNumber: 0,        // button number (0=left, 1=right, 2=middle) or finger ID for touch
    lastClickPos: { 
        x: 456,                         // the x coordinate of the last mouseDown event
        y: 201              // the y coordinate of the last mouseDown event
    },
    lastClickElapsed: 201   // the number of milliseconds since the last mouseDown
}

.fi
.PP

.PP
Location and time since the last mouseDown event are provided to make it easier to detect double-clicks, dragging, and gestures\&.

.PP
\fBNote\fP
.RS 4
on a touch device mouse moved events are only generated when the user is touching the device, and each finger touching is treated like a separate mouse button, with the button number based on the order the fingers touched the device\&.

.PP
A SpriteLayer has the ability to automatically handle these mouse events and generate \fBpdg\&.eventType_SpriteTouch\fP for any Sprite that was clicked on, or pass these on as mouse events if no Sprite was hit\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBpdg\&.eventType_MouseDown\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.eventType_MouseUp\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.eventType_MouseMove\fP 

.PP
\fBpdg\&.eventType_SpriteTouch\fP 

